Rossmann Sales Forecasting

Paulina KuÅ‚akowska, Ewa Weychert

1. Introduction

Sales forecasting is one of the key business challenges. Store sales are influenced by many factors, such as promotions, competition, holidays, location, or day of the week. Reliable sales prediction enables stores to create effective marketing strategies and maximize their profits. This project aims at finding the most appropriate model for predicting sales and its most important predictors.

1.1. Research problem

The research questions we are going to answer along the data analysis and building the models are to what extent the level of sales among 1,115 stores (cross-sectional data) is affected by factors like promotion, type of a store and its assortment, and competitor data. What should be the most appropriate model for foresting drugstore sales and what features should be included in the process?

1.2. Methodology

After data preprocessing, we focus on feature analysis supported with some Exploratory Data Analysis as well as own intuition insights. We come with some extra features to our initial dataset and we code the data to be convenient for our models. We evaluate each model and implement some tuning. The tested methods are Regression Trees, Random Forest, and Gradient Boosting Machine. The best model and predictor are distinguished.

2. Data preparation

In this part, we deliver some missing data handling and feature extraction. Only the Kaggleâ€™s train.csv data is used, which consists of historical data including Sales. It is then combined with supplemental information about the stores. Our raw data has over 1mln sales observations and 9 variables, while the store information contains 8 variables. Each set is paired by the store id key.

2.1. Data description and preprocessing

The structure of the dataset is as follows.It combines sales data and store characteristics, such as type of store, its assortment, whether its open on holidays, the promotions of a particular store and information about its competition.

Data description - Historical sales dataset (Train.csv):

  • Store - a unique Id for each store
  • Day of Week - an indicator for the day of week: 1 = Monday, 2 = Tuesday â€¦ 7 = Sunday
  • Date - MM/DD/YY
  • Sales - the turnover on a given day
  • Customers - the number of customers on a given day
  • Open - an indicator for whether the store was open: 0 = closed, 1 = open
  • Promo - indicates whether a store is running a promo on that day: 0 = no promo, 1 = have promo
  • StateHoliday - indicates a state holiday: a = public holiday, b = Easter holiday, c = Christmas, 0 = None
  • SchoolHoliday - indicates if the (Store, Date) was affected by the closure of public schools: 0 = No, 1 = Yes

Data description - Store Information (Store.csv)

  • StoreType - 4 different store models: a, b, c, d
  • Assortment - describes an assortment level: a = basic, b = extra, c = extended
  • CompetitionDistance - distance in meters to the nearest competitor store
  • CompetitionOpenSince[Month/Year] - gives the approximate year and month of the time the nearest competitor was opened
  • Promo2 - a continuing and consecutive promotion for some stores: 0 = store is not participating, 1 = store is participating
  • Promo2Since[Year/Week] - describes the year and calendar week when the store started participating in Promo2

Source: https://www.kaggle.com/c/rossmann-store-sales/data

There is no missing data in the train (sales) set. We only need to deal with NAs in the store data.

For given data, such us Year, Week, Month, wich are non-numeric variables, imputing missing values with mode (the value which occurs most of the time) is a common choice.

# filling NAs for each variable with missings with the mode
# imputing the mode
store$CompetitionDistance[is.na(store$CompetitionDistance)] <- 250
store$CompetitionOpenSinceMonth[is.na(store$CompetitionOpenSinceMonth)] <- 8
store$CompetitionOpenSinceYear[is.na(store$CompetitionOpenSinceYear)] <- 2013
store$Promo2SinceYear[is.na(store$Promo2SinceYear)] <- 2012
store$Promo2SinceWeek[is.na(store$Promo2SinceWeek)] <- 22

plot_missing(store)

Then, after merging sales and store data, we extract the day, month, year and week (from the beggining of year) variables from the date. We also add new variable, which is the logarithm of sales and will be predicted.

# combining the store and sales data into one set
sales <- merge(data, store, by = "Store")

# we seperate month and year variables from date
sales$Year <- as.numeric(strftime(sales$Date, format="%y")) 
sales$Month <- as.numeric(strftime(sales$Date, format="%m"))
sales$Day <- as.numeric(strftime(sales$Date, format="%d"))
sales$Week <- as.numeric(strftime(sales$Date, format="%W"))

# we want to order sales by dates
sales <- sales[order(sales$Date),]
## [1] "English_United States.1252"

2.2 Exploratory Data Analysis

From the density plot, we see that our data is slightly right skewed. The frequency of sales seems to be higher when its values are low.

To account for the variability of sales data, we would like to implement the logarithm of sales variable in forecasting, which is considered a common approach when dealing with sales time series and is less sensitive to high sales.

After taking the logarithm, the distribution of sales is less skewed and we manage to flatten the data.

As one may expect, the correlation between sales and customers is high and positive. When we illustrate the scatterplot, we observe that the type of store seem to correpsond to the dispertion of the correlation, meaning each store type slightly differs in correlation with the number of customers. We may, therefore, suspect the store type to be a somewhat significant factor influencig the level of sales for a store, and thus worth keeping.

The Promo (short-term/daily promotion) and Promo2 (consecutive long-term promotion) seem to also infleunce the level of sales, however, in quite opposite manners.

2.3 Feature Engineering

We further inspect the significance of Promo factor using the Welch Two Sample t-test and find that promotions have a significant impact on sales, which are about 40 percent higher on average during promotions.

t.test(sales[sales$Promo,]$Sales,sales[!sales$Promo,]$Sales)

We see no similar effect for the Promo2 variable. In fact, the consecutive promotion does not seem to influence the sales volumen that much. We consider this variable rather redundant and refuse to include it in our models. We also exclude the PromoInterval variable

When taking into account the averages sales, the sales for certain stores that are open on Sundays are highest on Sundays. Although the day of week variable does not have much influence on sales, as the sales are rather equally distributed over the week, incorporating information of whether a store is closed or open on Sundays may have a significant impact on forecasting the storeâ€™s performance when it comes to sales. Therefore, instead of DayOfWeek and Open variables we rather introduce the isSunday variable, indicating whether sales are on Sunday or not. Stores in Germany are mostly closed on Sundays expect from few time a year. We may therefore suspect during these times very high sales levels, what explains the high sales average on Sundays.

Sales are highest on Mondays and Sundays and fairly equally distributed over the rest of days within the week. Their level, in constrast, is lowest on Saturdays, which can result from the fact that some stores close earlier on Saturday.

# introducing the 'isSunday' variable using one_hot_encoder() function to create binary response

hot_encoder <- build_encoding(sales, cols = "DayOfWeek")

# renaming the name of the column fo DayOfWeek.7 to isSunday
colnames(sales)[colnames(sales)=="DayOfWeek.7"] <- "isSunday"
sales[,30] <- sales[,30] == 1

Finally, we consider the state holidays as important factors, but the school holiday variable not worth including in modelling.

When looking closer on the two-months-period, we observe weekly patterns in sales trend.

Intuitively, the best candidate for a predictor for future sales could be past sales. Because Customers variable is already a significant factor influencing sales, why not add information aboue avarage sales per customer on a particular day? This could be an indicator of the significance of introducting promotion campaigns and some regular customer offers that aim at cumulating the number of loyal customers and their baskets of transactions. We are going to use both the Customers and SalesPerCustomer variables in our model, because they influence the level of sales strongly. However, because of high correlation it may seem like making predictions of something which is already known, as the customers correspond to the value of sales. Therefore, to account for the look-ahead bias, we will use the lagged customers and sales per customer data, taking the observations for the same day, but week before.

# Extracting one-week lagged observations for customers, adding lagged sales per customer
myDf <- as.data.frame(sales)
myDf <- slide(myDf, "Customers", GroupVar = "Store", NewVar = "CustomersLag7", slideBy = -7)
## 
## Remember to order myDf by Store and the time variable before running.

3. Regression

3.1. Regression Tree

For our analysis, we only use the train.csv set provided by Kaggle. We treat it as our initial dataset, and divide it on our own into new train and test sets in proportions 70% vs.Â 30% respectively. We build a model formula with the following components:

model.formula <- logSales ~ SalesPerCustomerLag7 + CustomersLag7 + Assortment + Promo + StoreType + CompetitionDistance + isSunday + Year + Month + Week + Day + StateHoliday + CompetitionOpenSinceMonth + CompetitionOpenSinceYear + Promo2SinceWeek + Promo2SinceYear

The above formula is further used in every machine learning method.

# Creating data partition
set.seed(12345678)
index <- createDataPartition(sales$Sales, p = 0.7, list = FALSE)

train <- sales[index, ]

test <-  sales[-index, ]

# to fasten computations randomly choose 10000 observations
# from the original training data set
set.seed(12345678)
train2 <- train[sample(1:nrow(train),
                                size = 10000,
                                replace = FALSE),]

The we use the train set sample to train our initial regression tree model.

regTree_model <- rpart(formula = model.formula, 
                        data = train2, 
                        method = "anova")

# Tuning and cross-validation

# Cross-validation 
cv_ctrl3 <- trainControl(method = "cv",
                         number = 3)
cv.grid <- expand.grid(cp = seq(0, 0.03, 0.001))

set.seed(12345678)
regTree_tuned <- train(model.formula,
                  data = train2, 
                  method = "rpart", 
                  trControl = cv_ctrl3,
                  tuneGrid = cv.grid)

4. Final models evaluation & conclusions

Given all the best models for each machine learning method, we receive the following results for the test set:

Regression Tree

MSE RMSE MAE R2
0.0839876 0.2898061 0.2215274 0.5383356

Random Forest

MSE RMSE MAE R2
0.0528859 0.2299693 0.1726794 0.7092959

Gradient Boosting Machine

MSE RMSE MAE R2
0.0633022 0.2515992 0.1907693 0.6520395

The best performing algorithm seems to be the Random Forest after tuning, with the lowest RMSE and highest R^2, however, it suffers from some overfitting. The closest in terms of train and test predictions is the Regression Tree model with no instance of overfit.

Suprisingly, the best predictor of sales turned out to be not the past sales data nor number of customers. In fact, the most valuable factor is the promotion (Promo) variable.
